{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Use Jamaican English|date=March 2012}} [[File:Lucille Mair 1980.jpg|thumb|Lucille Mair in 1980]] '''Dr. Lucille Mathurin Mair''', née Walrond (1924; Jamaica – 28 January 2009; [[Kingston, Jamaica]]), was a [[Jamaica]]n ambassador, author, diplomat and gender specialist.<ref name="Mona">{{cite web|url=http://myspot.mona.uwi.edu/history/ambassador-lucille-mair|title=Ambassador Lucille Mair|publisher=Department of History, [[University of the West Indies]]|accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref>
==Education and career== Mair obtained a first degree in history at [[London University]]. In 1974 she obtained a Ph.D. in history from the [[University of the West Indies]] with a dissertation entitled "A Historical Study of Women in Jamaica 1655–1844",<ref name="Mona"/> about which [[Verene Shepherd]] has said: "Over a period of three decades, it became the most sought-after unpublished work among students and scholars of Caribbean history and culture."<ref>Verene A. Shepherd, [http://old.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20090131/letters/letters4.html "Tribute to Lucille Mathurin Mair"] (letter to the Editor), ''The Gleaner'', 31 January 2009. Retrieved 4 June 2018.</ref>
Mair served as Assistant Secretary-General in the office of the United Nations Secretary in 1979, from which she performed the role of Secretary-General for the [[World Conference on Women, 1980|World Conference of the United Nations Decade for Women]] held in 1980 in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=CARICOM>{{cite web|url=http://www.caricom.org/jsp/projects/personalities/lucille_mair.jsp?menu=projects|title=Triennial Award: Dr. Lucille Mathurin Mair|publisher=[[Caribbean Community|Caribbean Community (CARICOM)]]|accessdate=30 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218234754/http://www.caricom.org/jsp/projects/personalities/lucille_mair.jsp?menu=projects|archivedate=18 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> From 1981 to 1982, she served as special advisor to the [[United Nations Children's Fund]] (UNICEF) on Women's Development at the level of assistant secretary general.<ref name="JO-obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/145429_Ambassador-Lucille-Mair-is-dead|title=Ambassador Lucille Mair is dead|date=29 January 2009|newspaper=[[The Jamaica Observer]]|accessdate=30 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029183812/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/145429_Ambassador-Lucille-Mair-is-dead|archivedate=29 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She then went on to served as Secretary-General of the United Nations Conference on Palestine from 1982 to 1987. She was the Permanent Representative of Jamaica to the [[United Nations]] from 1992 to 1995 and was also Ambassador to [[Cuba]].<ref name="Mona"/>
Mair died on 28 January 2009 at her home in [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]].<ref name="JO-obit"/>
==Awards== The International [[Institute of Social Studies]] (ISS) awarded its honorary doctorate to Lucille Mair in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iss.nl/about_iss/honorary_fellows/lucille_mair/|title=Lucille Mair|last=ISS Library staff |publisher=[[Institute of Social Studies]]|accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref> In 1996, she received [[CARICOM]]'s Triennial Award for Women.<ref name=CARICOM/>
