The '''Maine accent''' is the local traditional pronunciation of [[Eastern New England English]] in parts of Maine, especially along the [[Down East|"Down East"]] and [[Mid Coast|"Mid Coast" seaside regions]].<ref>Wolfram, Walt; Ward, Ben (eds.) (2006). ''American Voices: How dialects differ from coast to coast''. Malden, MA ; Oxford: Blackwell Publishing. p. 73.</ref> It is characterized by a variety of features, particularly among older speakers, including ''r''-dropping ([[rhoticity in English|non-rhoticity]]), resistance to the [[horse–hoarse merger]],<ref name="Labov">{{citation|last=Labov|first=William|authorlink=William Labov|last2=Ash|first2=Sharon|last3=Boberg|first3=Charles|year=2006|title=The Atlas of North American English|location=Berlin|publisher=Mouton-de Gruyter|isbn=3-11-016746-8|pages=226–7}}</ref> a deletion or "breaking" of certain syllables, and some unique vocabulary. This traditional Maine accent is rapidly declining; a 2013 study of [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] speakers found the horse–hoarse merger to be currently embraced by all ages and the [[cot–caught merger]] to be resisted,<ref>Ryland, Alison (2013). "A Phonetic Exploration of the English of Portland, Maine". Swarthmore College.</ref> despite being typical among other Eastern New England speakers, even reported in the 1990s in Portland itself.<ref name="Labov"/> In the northern region of Maine along the Quebec border, Franco-Americans may show French-language influences in their English.<ref>Wolfram, Walt; Ward, Ben (eds.) (2006). ''American Voices: How dialects differ from coast to coast''. Malden, MA ; Oxford: Blackwell Publishing. p. 74-75.</ref>
==Phonology== Maine English often features [[phonetic change]] or [[phonological change]] of certain characteristics. One such characteristic is that, like in all traditional Eastern New England English, Maine English pronounces the "r" sound only when it comes before a vowel, but not before a consonant or in any final position. For example, "car" may sound to listeners like "cah" and "Mainer" like "Mainah."<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref>
Also, as in much New England English, the final "-ing" ending in multi-syllable words sounds more like "-in," for example, in ''stopping'' {{IPA|[ˈstɑpɪn]}} and ''starting'' {{IPA|[ˈstäːʔɪn]}}.<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref>
The Maine accent follows the pronunciation of [[Eastern New England English]], with the following additional features: *{{IPAc-en|ɜr}} before a consonant is {{IPA|[ə~ɜ~ɛ]}}. *Single-syllable words ending with [[R-colored vowel]]s (such as {{IPAc-en|ɪər|,_|ɛər|,_|ɔːr}}) sometimes become two syllables. The vowel loses its R-coloration. That includes {{IPAc-en|ɪər}} as in ''here'' {{IPA-all|ˈhɪ.(j)ɜ||"Here".ogg}}, {{IPAc-en|ɛər}} as in ''there'' {{IPA-all|ˈðeɪ.(j)ɜ||"There".ogg}}, and (as mentioned above) {{IPAc-en|oʊ|r}} as in ''more'' {{IPA-all|ˈmoʊ.(w)ɜ||"More".ogg}}.<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> **{{IPAc-en|ɔːr}} is {{IPA|[ɒə]}} in words like ''horse'' ({{IPA|[hɒəs]}} "hoss"), ''war'' ({{IPA|[wɒə]}} "waw"), ''north'' ({{IPA|[nɒəθ]}} "nawth"), or ''porch'' ({{IPA|[pʰɒətʃ]}} "pawch"). **{{IPAc-en|oʊ|r}} is {{IPA|[ˈoʊ(w)ə]}} in words like ''hoarse'' ({{IPA|[ˈhoʊ(w)əs]}} "hoe-us"), ''wore'' ({{IPA|[ˈwoʊ(w)ə]}} "whoa-uh"), ''more'' ({{IPA|[ˈmoʊ(w)ə]}} "mow-uh"), or ''shore'' ({{IPA|[ˈʃoʊ(w)ə]}} "show-uh"). *Many speakers also produce a dipping tone when they pronounce the extended word; they lower their tone for the first syllable and raise it for the second syllable.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} The phrase "[[You can't get there from here]]," coined in an episode of the mid-1900s humor stories collection [[Bert & I]], is a quintessential example of the principle of syllable extension.
==Lexicon== The traditional Maine dialect has a fairly rich vocabulary. Some of this vocabulary is shared with other New England dialects, however much of it is specific to Maine. This vocabulary includes, but is not limited to, the following terms: {{div col}} *''apiece''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; an undetermined distance (as in "He lives down the road apiece") *''ayuh''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref><ref>{{harvcoltxt|VisitMaine|2015}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|ˈ|eɪ|ə}}, {{IPAc-en|ˈ|eɪ|j|ə}} &mdash; yes; okay; sure; that's right *''beetah''<ref name=bdn>{{cite web |url=http://midcoastmillennial.bangordailynews.com/2015/06/01/home/the-outta-statahs-guide-to-maine-slang/ |title=The Outta Statah’s Guide to Maine Slang |last=Norman |first=Abby |website= |publisher=BDN |accessdate=16 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; a (beaten up) motor vehicle with value so diminished by extensive road salt corrosion there is little concern about additional collision damage from driving on icy roads *''bug''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; lobster *''bureau''<ref name=can>{{cite web |url=http://homes.chass.utoronto.ca/~cpercy/courses/eng6365-reid.htm |title=English in Maine: The Mythologization and Commodification of a Dialect |last=Reid |first=Lindsay Ann |website= |publisher=University of Toronto |accessdate=17 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; a dresser or chest of drawers *''Kout!''<ref name=fem>{{cite web |url=http://matadornetwork.com/pulse/mini-guide-maine-english/ |title=The 25 Funniest Expressions in Maine |last=Thieme |first=Emma |website=matador network |publisher= |accessdate=17 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; a warning to be alert (Look out!) *''chupta?''<ref name=fem/> &mdash; What are you doing? (What are you up to?) *''culch''<ref name=dem>{{cite web |url=http://downeast.com/dialects/ |title=What it Means to Talk Like a Mainer |last=Erard |first=Michael |website= |publisher=Down East |accessdate=17 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; trash or rubbish *''cunning'' (''kunnin'')<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref><ref>{{harvcoltxt|VisitMaine|2015}}</ref> &mdash; cute (as in "She's a cunnin' one, she is") *''cutter'' (''kuttah'') &mdash; an active child or younger person (from comparison to the harbor behavior of small, maneuverable cutters among larger ships) *''dinner pail'' (''dinnah pail'')<ref name=can/> &mdash; lunch box *''dite'' &mdash; a tiny amount (as in "Just a dite") *''door yard'' (''doah yahd'')<ref name=bdn/> &mdash; the yard or occupant's space outside a dwelling's exterior door -- sometimes decorated with ornamental plants, and often used for temporary storage of tools, toys, sleds, carts, or bicycles *''Down East''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|VisitMaine|2015}}</ref> &mdash; loosely refers to the coastal regions of [[Hancock County, Maine|Hancock]] and [[Washington County, Maine|Washington]] counties; because that boats traveled ''down''wind from Boston to Maine (as in "I'm headin' Down East this weekend") - also used in [[Canadian English#Other Canadianisms|Canadian English]], possibly as the aforementioned Maine counties are close to parts of [[Atlantic Canada]]. *''dressing'' (''dressin'')<ref name=can/> &mdash; application of manure to a garden *''dry-ki''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bangordailynews.com/2012/03/08/living/local-language-alive-and-well-in-maine/ |title=Dictionary includes words only a Mainer would use |last=Burnham |first=Emily |website= |publisher=BDN |accessdate=17 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; an accumulation of floating dead wood on the downwind shore of a lake *''fart'' (''old faht'')<ref name=can/> &mdash; an inflexibly meticulous individual *''flatlander''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|VisitMaine|2015}}</ref> &mdash; visitor from elsewhere, often from Massachusetts due to its flat topography *''frap''<ref name=bdn/> &mdash; a milkshake with ice cream (from frappe) *''gawmy''<ref name=msd>{{cite web |url=http://gonewengland.about.com/od/maine/a/aa-speak-mainer.htm |title=Speak like a Mainer |last=Fowles |first=Debby |website=about travel |publisher= |accessdate=17 August 2016 }}</ref> &mdash; clumsy and awkward *''honkin''<ref name=msd/> &mdash; extraordinarily large *''hot top''<ref name=can/> &mdash; asphaltic pavement *''Italian''<ref name=msd/> &mdash; [[submarine sandwich]] *''jimmies''<ref name=can/> &mdash; colored sugar dessert sprinkles *''johnny''<ref name=can/> &mdash; hospital gown *''kife''<ref name=bdn/> &mdash; to steal (usually a small, useful item of low cost) *''lawn sale'' &mdash; yard sale *''nippy''<ref name=bdn/> &mdash; cold enough to stiffen one's nipples *''notional''<ref name=can/> &mdash; stubborn *''numb''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; dumb; stupid (as in "Numb son you got there") *''pahtridge'' &mdash; [[ruffed grouse]] (''Bonasa umbellus'') (from partridge) *''pekid''<ref name=fem/> &mdash; feeling unwell *''pisser'' (''pissah'') &mdash; something that is highly regarded; an [[intensifier]] (as in "She's a pissah, all right") *''pot''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; lobster trap *''prayer handle''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; knee *''[[quahog]]''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; thick-shelled clam (''Mercenaria mercenaria'') *''scrid''<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; a tiny piece; a little bit *''right out straight''<ref name=msd/> &mdash; too busy to take a break *''spleeny''<ref name=can/> &mdash; overly sensitive *''squaretail'' (''squayhtail'') &mdash; [[brook trout]] (''Salvelinus fontinalis'') *''steamers'' (''steamahs'')<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Fowles|2015}}</ref> &mdash; [[soft-shell clam]]s (''Mya arenaria'') *''stove in/stove up'' &mdash; [[Glossary of nautical terms|nautical term]] meaning bashed in (as in "Stoved all ta hell") *'''taint'' &mdash; contraction meaning 'it ain't' *'''tis'' &mdash; contraction meaning 'it is' *''togue'' &mdash; [[lake trout]] (''Salvelinus namaycush'') *''wail on'' &mdash; to hit (something) hard and repeatedly *''wicked'' &mdash; very (as in 'it's wicked cold out') {{div col end}}
==In popular culture== * Maine humorist [[Marshall Dodge]] (1935-1982) based much of his humor from the Maine dialect, beginning first with his involvement with the series ''[[Bert & I]]'', a "[[Down East]]" collection of humor stories created during the 1950s and 1960s . * Well-known author, musician, and former television broadcaster [[Tim Sample]] is known nationwide for his use of Maine vernacular.
