{{ Infobox archaeological culture |name = Soanian |map = Soan near Adiala.JPG |mapalt = |altnames = |horizon = |region = [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]] |period = [[Lower Paleolithic]] |dates = 500,000 – 125,000 BP {{cn|date=September 2017}} |typesite = [[Soan River]] |majorsites = [[Adiala]], [[Chauntra]], [[Khasala Kalan]], [[Khasala Khurd]], [[Sivalik Hills]] |extra = |precededby = [[Acheulean]] |followedby = [[Mousterian]] }}
The '''Soanian''' is an archaeological culture of the [[Lower Paleolithic]] in the [[Sivalik Hills|Siwalik region]] of the [[Indian subcontinent]].<ref name="sites.google.com">{{cite journal |last1=Lycett |first1=Stephen J. |title=Is the Soanian techno-complex a Mode 1 or Mode 3 phenomenon? A morphometric assessment |journal=Journal of Archaeological Science |date=2007 |volume=34 |issue=9 |pages=1434–1440 |doi=10.1016/j.jas.2006.11.001|url=http://sites.google.com/site/sjlycett/Lycett_2007_Soan.pdf}}</ref> Contemporary to the [[Acheulean]], it is named after the [[Soan River|Soan Valley]] in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1312059|title=Pakistan: The lesser-known histories of an ancient land}}</ref> Soanian sites are found along the Sivalik region in present-day [[India]], [[Nepal]] and [[Pakistan]].<ref name="The Sheffield Graduate Journal of Archaeology">Chauhan, Parth R., [https://assemblagejournal.files.wordpress.com/2017/05/an-overview-of-the-siwalik-acheulian.pdf] ''An Overview of the Siwalik Acheulian & Reconsidering Its Chronological Relationship with the Soanian – A Theoretical Perspective''.</ref>
==Findings== {{Location map+|India|width=350|float=left|caption=Map of the [[Indian subcontinent]] showing important sites of the Soanian culture.|places= {{Location map~|India|lat=32.016667|long=76.75|position=right|label_size=75|label=[[Chauntra]]}} {{Location map~|India|lat=33.44|long=72.973611|position=right|label_size=75|label=[[Khasala Kalan]]}} {{Location map~|India|lat=27.766667|long=82.4|position=right|label_size=75|label=[[Sivalik Hills]]}} {{Location map~|India|lat=33.016667|long=71.733333|position=left|label_size=75|label=[[Soan River]]}} }}
The term "Soan Culture" was first used by Hellmut De Terra in 1936,<ref name="MacCurdyPhiladelphia1969">{{cite book |author=Hellmut De Terra |editor=George Grant MacCurdy |title=Early man: as depicted by leading authorities at the International symposium, the Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia, March 1937 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t8yCCB8BHFcC&pg=PA267 |accessdate=16 October 2011 |year=1969 |isbn=978-0-8369-1184-8 |pages=267–}}</ref> but D. N. Wadia had identified the presence of these archaeological implements in 1928.<ref name="Oakley2007">{{cite book |author=Kenneth Oakley |title=Frameworks for Dating Fossil Man |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qrmOwp2swlgC&pg=PA224 |accessdate=16 October 2011 |date=30 April 2007 |origyear=1964 |publisher=Transaction Publishers |isbn=978-0-202-30960-6 |pages=224–}}</ref> Further archaeological research was conducted by Stephen Lycett in order to determine the morphometric assessment of the Soanian techno-complex. The result of this experiment concluded that the Soanian techno-complex contains a Mode 3 [[Levallois technique]] core component.<ref name="sites.google.com"/>
At [[Adiala]] and [[Khasala Kalan]], about {{convert|16|km|mi|abbr=on}} from [[Rawalpindi]] terrace on the bend of the river, hundreds of edged pebble tools were discovered. At [[Chauntra]] in [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[hand axe]]s and cleavers were found. Tools up to two million years old have been recovered. In the Soan River Gorge, many [[fossil]] bearing rocks are exposed on the surface. 14 million year old fossils of [[gazelle]], [[rhinoceros]], [[crocodile]], [[giraffe]] and [[rodent]]s have been found there. Some of these fossils are on display at the [[Pakistan Museum of Natural History]] in [[Islamabad]].
{{clear}}
==Spread across Shivalik Hills region== The earliest [[Paleolithic]] [[hominin]] archaeological site in the [[Indian subcontinent]] at the [[Soan Sakaser Valley]],<ref name="ppisv">{{cite book| last=Rendell| first=H. R.| last2=Dennell|first2=R. W. |last3=Halim|first3=M.| title=Pleistocene and Palaeolithic Investigations in the Soan Valley, Northern Pakistan| year=1989| page=364| series=British Archaeological Reports International Series| publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]| isbn=0-86054-691-8| oclc=29222688}}</ref> is part of Soanian, sites of are found in the [[Sivalik Hills]] across what are now India, Pakistan, and Nepal.<ref name="The Sheffield Graduate Journal of Archaeology"/><ref name="sites.google.com" />
